The '''etch pit density''' ('''EPD''') is a measure for the quality of [[semiconductor]] [[Wafer (electronics)|wafer]]s.<ref name="ZhuangEdgar2005">{{cite journal|last1=Zhuang|first1=D.|last2=Edgar|first2=J.H.|title=Wet etching of GaN, AlN, and SiC: a review|journal=Materials Science and Engineering: R: Reports|volume=48|issue=1|year=2005|pages=1–46|issn=0927796X|doi=10.1016/j.mser.2004.11.002}}</ref><ref name="Graff2013">{{cite book|author=Klaus Graff|title=Metal Impurities in Silicon-Device Fabrication|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WyXsCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA152|date=8 March 2013|publisher=Springer Science & Business Media|isbn=978-3-642-97593-6|pages=152–}}</ref>  

==Etching==
An [[Etching (microfabrication)|etch solution]] is applied on the surface of the wafer where the etch [[Rate (mathematics)|rate]] is increased at [[dislocation]]s of the [[crystal]] resulting in [[wikt:pit|pits]]. For [[GaAs]] one uses typically molten [[Potassium hydroxide|KOH]] at 450 degrees Celsius for about 40 minutes in a [[zirconium]] [[crucible]].  The [[density]] of the pits can be determined by [[Microscopy#Light Microscopy: the contrast issue|optical contrast microscopy]]. [[Silicon]] wafers have usually a very low density of < 100&nbsp;cm<sup>−2</sup> while semi-insulating GaAs wafers have a density on the order of 10<sup>5</sup> cm<sup>−2</sup>. 

==Germanium detectors==
High-purity [[Semiconductor_detector#Semiconductor_particle_detectors|Germanium detectors]] require the Ge crystals to be grown with a controlled range of dislocation density to reduce impurities. The etch pitch density requirement is typically within the range 10<sup>3</sup> to 10<sup>4</sup> cm<sup>−2</sup>.{{cn|date=December 2018}} 

==Standards==
The etch pit density can be determined according to [[DIN]] 50454-1 and [[ASTM]] F 1404.<ref name="DonekerRechenberg1998">{{cite book|author1=J. Doneker|author2=I. Rechenberg|title=Defect Recognition and Image Processing in Semiconductors 1997: Proceedings of the seventh conference on Defect Recognition and Image Processing, Berlin, September 1997|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ymeS1HIt1YYC&pg=PA248|date=1 January 1998|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=978-0-7503-0500-6|pages=248–}}</ref>

