{{Italic title}} '''''Moving Mountains: How One Woman and Her Community Won Justice From Big Coal''''' is a 2007 book published by the [[University Press of Kentucky]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Loeb |first=Penny |date=2007 |title=Moving Mountains: How One Woman and Her Community Won Justice from Big Coal |location=Lexington, KY |publisher=University Press of Kentucky |isbn=9780813124414 |jstor=j.ctt130jn7c}}</ref> The award-winning book is written by [[Virginia]] resident Penny Loeb, a former senior editor at [[U.S. News & World Report]] and a former [[investigative journalism|investigative reporter]] for ''[[Newsday]]''.<ref name=award>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|date=2008-07-27 |title='Moving Mountains' wins Foreword's prize for best environmental book |url=http://www.herald-dispatch.com/entertainment/outdoors/x2038882668/Moving-Mountains-wins-Forewords-prize-for-best-environmental-book |work=The Herald-Dispatch |location=Huntington, WV}}</ref><ref name=wash>{{cite news |last=Quigley |first=Joan |date=2007-09-26 |title=Digging Into a Coal Controversy |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/09/25/AR2007092502059.html |work=The Washington Post}}</ref>
Loeb spent nine years chronicling the difficult situation of Trish Bragg and other inhabitants of the [[West Virginia]] coalfields. In Loeb's analysis, these people are "caught between the economic opportunities provided by coal and the detriments to health and to quality of life that are so often the by-products of the coal industry". ''Moving Mountains'' is an account of the human and environmental costs of coal extraction, and the grassroots movement to mitigate those costs.<ref name=award/><ref name=wash/>
Loeb has received many awards for journalism, and was a finalist for the [[Pulitzer Prize]] in 1988 and for a [[National Magazine Award]] in 1993 and 1997.<ref name=award/>
