[[File:NewEnergyForAmericaLogo.jpg|thumb|New Energy For America]] {{seealso|Climate change in the United States}} '''New Energy for America''' was a plan led by [[Barack Obama]] and [[Joe Biden]] to invest in [[renewable energy]] sources, reduce reliance on [[North American energy independence|foreign oil]], address [[global warming]] issues, and create jobs for [[Americans]].
==History== The plan was presented in the [[Barack Obama presidential campaign, 2008]].
President Barack Obama in his [[inaugural address]] called for the expanded use of renewable energy to meet the twin challenges of energy security and climate change.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://apps1.eere.energy.gov/news/news_detail.cfm/news_id=12194 |title=EERE News: President Obama Calls for Greater Use of Renewable Energy |publisher=Apps1.eere.energy.gov |date=2009-01-21 |accessdate=2012-11-21}}</ref>
Obama issued a pair of [[memoranda]] on January 26 2009 to publish higher fuel economy standards for the model year 2011 cars and light trucks by the end of March<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/the_press_office/Presidential_Memorandum_fuel_economy/ |title=Presidential Memorandum - Fuel Economy &#124; The White House |publisher=Whitehouse.gov |date=2009-01-26 |accessdate=2012-11-21}}</ref> and lower [[greenhouse gas emission]]s<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/the_press_office/Presidential_Memorandum_EPA_Waiver/ |title=Presidential Memorandum - EPA Waiver &#124; The White House |publisher=Whitehouse.gov |date=2009-01-26 |accessdate=2012-11-21}}</ref> (to revisit a [[California]] [[waiver]] request that would allow that state to implement its own greenhouse gas emission rules for vehicles).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://apps1.eere.energy.gov/news/news_detail.cfm/news_id=12206 |title=EERE News: President Obama Issues Orders on Fuel Economy and GHG Regulations |publisher=Apps1.eere.energy.gov |date=2009-01-28 |accessdate=2012-11-21}}</ref>
==Content== The plan aimed to:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/agenda/energy_and_environment/ |title=Energy, Climate Change and Our Environment &#124; The White House |publisher=Whitehouse.gov |date= |accessdate=2012-11-21 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090429184849/http://www.whitehouse.gov/agenda/energy_and_environment/ |archivedate=2009-04-29 |df= }}</ref>{{Cite needed|date=May 2017}} *Help create five million new jobs by investing $150 billion over the next ten years to encourage private efforts to develop clean energy sources and technology. *Save more oil than the United States currently imports from the [[Middle East]] and [[Venezuela]] combined within 10 years.{{Quantify|date=March 2009}} *Put 1 million [[plug-in hybrid|Plug-In Hybrid cars]] on the road by 2015, with emphasis on cars built in the [[United States]]. *Generate 10 percent of the United States' electricity through renewable sources ([[renewable electricity]]) by 2012, and 25 percent by 2025. *Implement a [[cap-and-trade]] program to help reduce [[greenhouse gas]] emissions 80 percent by 2050.
==See also== *[[American Recovery and Reinvestment Plan]] *[[Clean Air Act (United States)|Clean Air Act]] *[[Corporate Average Fuel Economy]] (CAFE) *[[Energy Independence and Security Act of 2007]] *[[Energy Policy of the Obama Administration]] *[[United States energy independence]]
